[[File:Anthony-triangle.JPG|thumb|Anthony's Triangle]]The '''Anthony triangle'''<ref>{{cite book|
first=R N|last=Anthony|title=Planning and Control: a Framework for Analysis
|publisher= Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge MA|year=1965}}
</ref> (also '''Anthony's triangle''') is an organizational model. The triangle takes a hierarchical view of [[management]] structure, with many operational decisions at the bottom, some [[Tactical (disambiguation)|tactical]] decisions in the middle and few but important [[Strategy|strategic]] decisions at the top of the triangle. The higher in the triangle an item is, the more scope it covers and less precise it becomes. As items move down they become more detailed and apply more precisely.

It came to the attention of the [[information systems]] community through the work of George Gorry and [[Michael Scott Morton]].<ref>
{{cite journal
|last=Gorry|first=George Anthony
|first2=Michael S.|last2=Scott Morton
|title=A framework for management information systems
|journal=Sloan Management Review|volume=13|pages=21–36|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|year=1971}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20030614170155/http://mis.njit.edu/ullman/cis465/Articles/gorry.pdf 1989 reprint and retrospective commentary])</ref>

