'''Filipinos in Libya''' consist of [[migrant worker]]s in the construction, medical, and tourism sectors, as well as their children. From 5,000 people in 2003, the population had grown to 7,913 people by 2006; men outnumbered women by roughly two-to-one.<ref name="OPS"/><ref name="EN20030618">{{citation|url=http://www.ebalita.net/go/news/news.php?id=1321|title=Filipinos continue to bear SARS stigma in Libya|date=18 June 2003|accessdate=2008-10-10|periodical=eBalita News|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050224183127/http://www.ebalita.net/go/news/news.php?id=1321|archivedate=24 February 2005|df=}}</ref> During the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreak in 2003, Libyan authorities banned Filipinos from travelling to the country, causing 700 workers to lose jobs they had arranged.<ref name="EN20030618"/> Since 2005, the Philippine embassy has sponsored annual get-togethers for Filipino workers in the country in an attempt to foster a greater spirit of community among them.<ref>{{citation|periodical=Heroes Magazine|title=POLO Tripoli Holds 3 Programs for Independence, OWWA 25th Anniversary and Migrant Workers Day|date=22 October 2007|accessdate=2008-10-10|url=http://heroesmag.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=178&Itemid=36}}</ref> Filipinos working in Libya who bring their children with them are served by a school set up specifically for Filipinos, the Philippine Community School.<ref name="EN20030618"/> 794 Filipino children lived in Libya as of 2006.<ref name="OPS"/>

