{{Infobox ethnic group
|group     = Japanese expatriates in Singapore
|population= 35,982 (October 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/area/singapore/data.html|title=MOFA Japan|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
|langs     = Japanese; some study [[Singapore English|English]] or [[Mandarin Chinese]] as second languages<ref name="auto">{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|2003|p=127}}</ref>
|rels      = [[Buddhism]], [[Tenrikyo]]
|related-c = [[Japanese diaspora]]
}}
{{Ethnic Singapore sidebar}}
There is a large community of '''Japanese expatriates in Singapore''', consisting mostly of corporate employees and their families.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|2003|pp=116–117}}</ref> The first Japanese person to settle in [[Singapore]] was [[Otokichi|Yamamoto Otokichi]], who arrived in 1862.<ref name="auto1">{{harvnb|Tan|2008}}</ref> Larger-scale migration from Japan to Singapore is believed to have begun in the early 1870s, shortly after the [[Meiji Restoration]].<ref name="auto2">{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=25}}</ref>

==Migration history==

===Colonial era===
[[File:Otokichi Tomb.jpg|thumb|The tombstone of Otokichi, the first Japanese resident of Singapore]]

Singapore's first resident of Japanese origin is believed to be [[Otokichi|Yamamoto Otokichi]], from [[Mihama, Aichi]]. In 1832, he was working as a crewman on a Japanese boat which was caught in a storm and drifted across the Pacific Ocean; after a failed attempt to return home, he began to work for the British government as an interpreter. After earning [[British nationality law|British citizenship]], he settled in Singapore in 1862. He died five years later and was buried there.<ref name="auto1"/>

However, most early Japanese residents of Singapore consisted largely of prostitutes, who would later become known by the collective name of "''[[karayuki-san]]''". The earliest Japanese prostitutes are believed to have arrived 1870 or 1871; by 1889, there were 134 of them.<ref name="auto2"/> From 1895 to 1918, Japanese authorities turned a blind eye to the emigration of Japanese women to work in brothels in Southeast Asia.<ref name="auto3">{{harvnb|Warren|2003|p=35}}</ref> According to the Japanese consul in Singapore, almost all of the 450 to 600 Japanese residents of Singapore in 1895 were prostitutes and their pimps, or concubines; fewer than 20 were engaged in "respectable trades".<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=26}}</ref> In 1895, there were no Japanese schools or public organisations, and the Japanese consulate maintained only minimal influence over their nationals; brothel owners were the dominating force in the community. Along with victory in the [[First Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]], the Japanese state's increasing assertiveness brought changes to the official status of Japanese nationals overseas; they attained formal legal equality with Europeans.<ref>{{harvnb|Shiraishi|Shiraishi|1993|p=8}}</ref> That year, the Japanese community was also given official permission by the government to create [[Japanese Cemetery Park|their own cemetery]], on twelve acres of land in [[Serangoon]] outside of the urbanised area; in reality, the site had already been used as a burial ground for Japanese as early as 1888.<ref name="auto4">{{harvnb|Tsu|2002|p=96}}</ref>

However, even with these changes in their official status, the community itself remained prostitution-based.<ref name="auto5">{{harvnb|Shiraishi|Shiraishi|1993|p=9}}</ref> Prostitutes were the vanguard of what one pair of scholars describes as the "karayuki-led economic advance into Southeast Asia".<ref name="auto6">{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=21}}</ref> It was specifically seen by the authorities as a way to develop a Japanese economic base in the region; profits extracted from the prostitution trade were used to accumulate capital and diversify Japanese economic interests.<ref name="auto3"/> The prostitutes served as both creditors and customers to other Japanese: they loaned out their earnings to other Japanese residents trying to start businesses, and patronised Japanese tailors, doctors, and grocery stores.<ref name="auto6"/> By the time of the [[Russo-Japanese War]], the number of Japanese prostitutes in Singapore may have been as large as 700.<ref name="auto3"/> They were concentrated around Malay Street (now [[Middle Road, Singapore|Middle Road]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Warren|2003|p=41}}</ref> However, with Southeast Asia cut off from European imports due to [[World War I]], Japanese products began making inroads as replacements, triggering the shift towards retailing and trade as the economic basis of the Japanese community.<ref name="auto5"/>

Singapore abolished licensed Japanese prostitution in 1921.<ref>{{harvnb|Warren|2003|p=42, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Eo_Hav3qHYEC&pg=PA87 87]}}</ref> This was part of a larger governmental plan to entirely end legalised prostitution throughout the Malay Peninsula.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=66}}</ref> In spite of the ban, many attempted to continue their profession clandestinely; however, both the Singaporean and Japanese governments made efforts to clamp down on the trade.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=67}}</ref> By 1927, there remained roughly 126 independent Japanese prostitutes.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=68}}</ref> Most eventually left Singapore or moved on to other trades. Their departure coincided with a significant shift in the composition of the Japanese population there: the businesses they patronised, such as tailors and hairdresses, run largely by Japanese men, also shut their doors, and their proprietors left as well, to be replaced by salaried employees working in Japanese trading firms. Only 14 Japanese men worked in such professions in 1914, but by 1921 there were 1,478.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=69}}</ref> The shift would continue in the following decade: in 1919, 38.5% of Japanese in Singapore were commodity merchants and 28.0% company and bank employees, but by 1927, these proportions had shifted sharply, to 9.7% merchants and 62.9% employees.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=75}}</ref>

The Japanese population would peak in 1929 and then decline until 1933, as a result of the world-wide [[Great Depression]]. However, it would recover somewhat after that, aided by [[devaluation]] of the yen and the consequent increase in competitiveness of Japanese products in Southeast Asian markets.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|1993|p=63}}</ref> Even as other Japanese businesses suffered declines, the number of fishermen grew, from a small base of about 200 individuals in 1920 to a peak of 1,752 in 1936, accounting for between one-quarter and one-third of the resident Japanese population throughout the 1930s.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=94}}</ref>

===World War II and aftermath===
{{see also|Japanese occupation of Singapore}}
[[File:Count Terauchi Memorial.jpg|thumb|The Japanese cemetery in Singapore also houses the tombstone of Field Marshal Count [[Terauchi Hisaichi]], Commander of the Japanese Southern Forces during the World War II]]

All Japanese, whether civilian or military, were repatriated to Japan in 1947. Without anyone to maintain it, the Japanese cemetery fell into disrepair.<ref name="auto4"/> Graves were damaged due to the tropical climate as well as mistreatment by squatters and vandals.<ref>{{harvnb|Tsu|2002|p=97}}</ref> Japanese people returned to Singapore only slowly after the war. A few Japanese were issued landing permits in 1948 and 1949, but until 1953, the only Japanese permitted to reside in the country were diplomats and their families. Other Japanese could only be issued landing permits of a maximum validity of two months.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=160}}</ref> However, in the latter half of the 1950s, the restrictions on the entry of Japanese nationals were relaxed, and Japanese trading firms again set up offices in Singapore.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimizu|Hirakawa|1999|p=166}}</ref> The first post-war Japanese residents association, the Japanese Club, was founded in 1957 specifically with the aim of restoring the Japanese cemetery.<ref name="auto4"/>

===Independence era===
The Japanese community began to show significant growth again in the early 1970s, as Japanese businesses shifted manufacturing activities out of Japan into Southeast Asia.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|2003|p=117}}</ref> Since the mid-1980s, the vast majority of Japanese expatriates come to Singapore as families, with the father employed as a manager or engineer, while the wife [[Stay at home mom|stays at home with the children]]. A few men come without their families (a practise referred to in Japanese as ''[[:ja:単身赴任|tanshin funin]]'').<ref name="auto7">{{harnvb|Ben-Ari|Yong|2000|p=84}}</ref> Within the Japanese community, single women tend to be "doubly marginised": both at the office by Japanese businessmen's restrictive views of the role of women in the workplace, and in social life by the wives of those same businessmen.<ref>{{harnvb|Ben-Ari|Yong|2000|p=82}}</ref> Single Japanese women generally try to minimise their contacts with married Japanese women, even when the two live in the same neighbourhoods.<ref>{{harnvb|Ben-Ari|Yong|2000|p=103}}</ref>

Singapore and Japan celebrated 50 years of diplomatic relations in 2016 dubbed SJ50.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-japan-celebrate-50-years-of-friendship-at-sj50-gala-di-7746440|title=Singapore, Japan celebrate 50 years of friendship at SJ50 gala dinner|publisher=}}</ref>

The Japanese Association, Singapore (JAS) was established in 1915 and re-established in 1975 to promote exchange and interactions between Japanese and Singaporeans. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jas.org.sg/aboutus/about_en.html|title=The Japanese Association, Singapore|website=www.jas.org.sg}}</ref>

==Education==
[[File:Waseda Shibuya SH School.JPG|thumb|left|[[Waseda Shibuya Senior High School in Singapore]]]]
The Japanese community of Singapore are served by a number of Japanese-medium educational institutions, including a 400-student kindergarten, a 1,900-student primary school, a 700-student junior high school, and a 500-student senior high school, as well as twelve ''[[juku]]'' (cram schools) to prepare them for [[Higher education in Japan#College entrance|university entrance exams]].<ref name="auto7"/> The schools are situated near Japanese neighbourhoods, and all of the student body and staff are Japanese nationals. Only a small minority of Japanese families send their children to non-Japanese [[international school]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|2003|p=124}}</ref>

[[The Japanese School Singapore]] serves elementary and junior high students and the [[Waseda Shibuya Senior High School in Singapore]] (formerly Shibuya Makuhari Singapore School) serves high school students. Both schools hold annual festivals open to members of the public who are interested in Japanese culture.

The Japanese Supplementary School Singapore (JSS; シンガポール日本語補習授業校 ''Shingapōru Nihongo Hoshū Jugyō Kō''), a [[hoshuko|supplementary programme]], also operates in Singapore.<ref>"[https://web.archive.org/web/20140330214851/http://www.mext.go.jp/a_menu/shotou/clarinet/002/006/001/002/001.htm アジアの補習授業校一覧（平成25年4月15日現在）]" (). [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]]. Retrieved on February 13, 2015.</ref><ref>"[http://www.jss.edu.sg/contact  お問合せページ]." The Japanese Supplementary School Singapore. Retrieved on February 14, 2015.</ref>

==Religion==
A [[Tenrikyo]] church was established by Japanese expatriates in Singapore in 1922.<ref>{{harvnb|Hamrin|2000|p=196}}</ref> Their social volunteer work, especially with the handicapped, has been credited with helping to restore Japanese people's reputation in the eyes of [[Chinese Singaporean]]s, badly damaged by atrocities during the [[Japanese occupation of Singapore]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hamrin|2000|p=211}}</ref> However, Tenrikyo remains largely a religion of Japanese expatriates, not of average Singaporeans.<ref>{{harvnb|Hamrin|2000|p=213}}</ref> Its association with [[Shinto]] has proven a disadvantage in attempts to spread it beyond the Japanese community.<ref name="auto8">{{harvnb|Hamrin|2000|p=214}}</ref>

Tenrikyo's main "rival" in Singapore is the [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] organisation [[Sōka Gakkai]]. Originally, its following was also restricted to the Japanese expatriate community.<ref name="auto8"/> However, it has had more success in outreach to local people, especially the ethnic Chinese community.<ref>{{harvnb|Clammer|2000|p=177}}</ref>

==Leisure==
As with Japanese in other countries, golf is a popular leisure activity among Japanese businesspeople in Singapore. As the Japanese community in Singapore grew in the 1970s, they applied political pressure to promote upgrading of existing golf courses and development of new ones. Though other expatriates, as well as members of the local upper-middle class, also spoke out in support of the improvement of golfing facilities in Singapore, generally the Japanese were described as making the most forceful demands.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|1998|p=141}}</ref> Japanese membership in golf associations grew so quickly that many established quotas on the number of foreign members with the express purpose of preventing their "inundation" with Japanese expatriates and tourists, and also established a [[price discrimination|two-track pricing system]], with higher prices for foreigners than locals.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|1998|p=142}}</ref> Due to the expense of playing golf in Singapore, lower-level Japanese personnel tend to head across the border into [[Johor Bahru]], [[Malaysia]] in search of cheaper green fees.<ref>{{harvnb|Ben-Ari|1998|p=146}}</ref>

Other popular leisure pursuits include tennis, swimming, [[Chinese as a foreign language|Mandarin]] and [[English as a foreign language|English language training]], and [[cooking school|cooking classes]].<ref name="auto"/>

