{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Steven Raphael | honorific_suffix = | native_name = Steven Paul Raphael | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age |1968|11|13}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2001109341.html | title=Steven Raphael | work=Library of Congress | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = [[University of California, Berkeley]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = University of California, Berkeley (Ph.D., 1996) | thesis_title = An analysis of the spatial determinants and long-term consequences of youth joblessness | thesis_url = http://escholarship.org/uc/item/9g71739m | thesis_year = 1996 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[Goldman School of Public Policy]] Faculty Teaching Award, Award for Excellence in Housing and Development Research from the [[Association of Public Policy Analysis and Management]] and the [[U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (both in 2001) | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Steven Paul Raphael''' (born November 13, 1968) is an American economist and Professor of Public Policy in the [[Goldman School of Public Policy]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], as well as an adjunct fellow at the [[Public Policy Institute of California]]. He is also a research fellow at the [[University of Michigan]] National Poverty Center, the [[University of Chicago Crime Lab]], and the [[Institute for the Study of Labor]] in [[Bonn, Germany]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gspp.berkeley.edu/directories/faculty/steven-raphael | title=Steven Raphael | work=University of California, Berkeley | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>
==Education== Raphael received his B.A. from [[San Diego State University]] in 1990 and his Ph.D. from University of California, Berkeley in 1996.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ppic.org/content/cv/Raphael.pdf | title=Steven Raphael CV | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>
==Research== Raphael's research focuses on economic aspects of low-wage labor markets, housing, and [[incarceration in the United States]], as well as, more recently, the social consequences of [[mass incarceration]] in the United States.<ref name=ppic/> He has also studied the effectiveness of incarceration in decreasing crime in the modern United States, and has contended that "We have a fairly strong body of research that suggests as the incarceration rate goes up, the effectiveness of incarceration as a crime-control tool goes down."<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/16/423257919/is-it-possible-to-let-more-people-out-of-prison-and-keep-crime-down | title=Is It Possible To Let More People Out Of Prison, And Keep Crime Down? | work=NPR | date=16 July 2015 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Kaste, Martin}}</ref> In 2014, he and [[Michael Stoll]] reported that incarceration was less effective at reducing crime when the prison population was high than when it was low.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/30/business/economy/in-the-us-punishment-comes-before-the-crimes.html?_r=0 | title=In the U.S., Punishment Comes Before the Crimes | work=New York Times | date=30 April 2014 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Porter, Eduardo}}</ref> He has also co-authored studies with Stoll and Magnus Lofstrom finding that when California reduced its incarceration rate significantly, this reduction seemed to have no effect on [[violent crime]] rates in the state, and that it had a modest effect on [[property crime]], especially auto theft.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lofstrom|first1=M.|last2=Raphael|first2=S.|title=Incarceration and Crime: Evidence from California's Public Safety Realignment Reform|journal=The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science|date=18 February 2016|volume=664|issue=1|pages=196–220|doi=10.1177/0002716215599732}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://psmag.com/california-s-criminal-justice-experiment-15b07de95fed#.bqtsy88xp | title=California’s Criminal Justice Experiment | work=Pacific Standard | date=24 February 2016 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Wheeling, Kate}}</ref> His research has also suggested that wages for low-skilled white American workers in [[Arizona]] declined during 2008 and 2009, but that the median incomes of employed workers in this group rose by 6% during this time.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-thorny-economics-of-illegal-immigration-1454984443 | title=The Thorny Economics of Illegal Immigration | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=9 February 2016 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Davis, Bob}}</ref>
==Editorial activities== Raphael is the former [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[Industrial Relations: A Journal of Economy and Society]]''.<ref name=ppic>{{cite web | url=http://www.ppic.org/main/bio.asp?i=160 | title=Steven Raphael | work=Public Policy Institute of California | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>
